	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Bregalad</b> [ Wed Jan 14, 2009 7:47 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />/CE and /OE have the same function on an EPROM : If they are both low you can read data from the EPROM and if any of them is high you can't.
<br />
<br />However, they are different on RAMs, where /CE and /WR should be low to write to the chip, while both /CE and /OE should be low to read data. As long as /CE is high the chip ignores everything.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


